===subject:I agree with all except....
===from:Vickie Saunders
===date:Mon Apr 28 12:36:25 2003
===message:It's true that television does not capture ALL aspects of an era and reinforces stereotypes but I believe shows like "I Love Lucy" were acurrate to the reality of most white women in the 1950s.  Lucy was a housewife, who when the need for money arose or when she was bored worked outside the home.  Ricky was the breadwinner however.  I think another aspect television accurately captured of the housewife was Lucy's ocassional dissatisfication at staying home.  Why else would Lucy and Ethel concoct the schemes they did?

My maternal grandmother was one of those housewives in the 1950s and she told me there was not much else for women to do in those days.  She said women were almost always expected to marry and have kids.  And for her (being a black woman) the only work she was able to do was domestic servitude.  To cure her boredom she took to watching soap operas. My grandfather was the breadwinner, he had his own plumbing business.
=========yorg=========
